We willStore every conversation, result, tool output, and useful fact in a database, 
then let Jarvis check that first before calling APIs again.

At first Jarvis may be slower because it is:

learning
storing
organizing
building memory

Later it gets faster because it can:

reuse old answers
avoid repeated API calls
remember your projects and habits
search its own database first

Every saved answer should have:

the answer
when it was saved
where it came from
whether it can expire


Before reusing an old answer, Jarvis should ask:

Is this the kind of thing that changes?
How old is this saved answer?
Should I refresh it before answering?


We can use threading

one thread saves new conversations
one thread searches old memory
one thread handles live response
one thread checks whether old cached answers need refreshing

But for heavy CPU work, multiprocessing is usually better.






